I switched all my repositories remote URLs using the "Convert all to SSH" action in the Sourcetree home screen.

It converted them to
{noformat}
mycompany ssh://git@bitbucket.org:mycompany/hello.git (fetch)
mycompany ssh://git@bitbucket.org:mycompany/hello.git (push){noformat}
But when I do an action related to my remotes, I get this error

 
{noformat}
▶ git fetch mycompany
ssh: Could not resolve hostname bitbucket.org:mycompany: nodename nor servname provided, or not known
fatal: Could not read from remote repository.Please make sure you have the correct access rights
and the repository exists.{noformat}
 

I had to change the remote URL to remove the "ssh://", and it works again
{noformat}
mycompany git@bitbucket.org:mycompany/hello.git (fetch)
mycompany git@bitbucket.org:mycompany/hello.git (push){noformat}
FYI, I have 12 repositories multiplied by 3 remotes each, multiplied by 2 operations (push/pull). 72 remote urls to change. I don't know what went wrong, but I'm so happy.

I have been doing a lot of minor commits with no messages in the terminal, using

{{git commit -m '' --allow-empty-message}}

I can see the list of commits in the history in SourceTree:

{{[Missing-Commits-1.png]}}

Now that I have the finished code, I want to squash together those small commits to one big commit and write a proper commit message.

I click on the commit before the small commits, and choose "Interactively rebase children of ...."

In the list of commits, only two commits with messages are shown

{{[Missing-Commits-2.png]}}

From the first picture, you can see there should be two commits between *a65167e* and *5cffde0* but they do not appear in the list of commits for interactive rebase

When I run this command from terminal to identify file renames,
{code:java}
git add -A {code}
all the files are displayed in SourceTree correctly as renames, but after commit, all the renamed files will be staged again as removed. It will commit renames as new files and leave old file names as deleted. History between file renames will be broken and only way back is to hard reset head and do everything from command line.
{code:java}
git reset HEAD~ {code}
This is serious problem.
